More than 2000 people have been killed and more than 500 000 others displaced in the violence, according to the International Committee of the Red Cross. Nigeria's Minister of Foreign Affairs, Geoffrey Onyeama, visited Mozambique over the weekend and met Prime Minister Carlos Agostinho do Ros√°rio. Onyeama said Nigeria was ready to share its experience of fighting Islamist militants and provide support to Mozambique. The visit was part of a diplomatic tour to southern Africa countries to mobilise support for Nigeria's bid to chair the peace and security council of the African Union. Tanzania, South Africa and Burkina Faso are also vying for the seat. Elections will be held during AU's summit scheduled for later this week. --BBC--